.TH "SET.SIZE" "3JS" "July 20, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Set.size \- Set.prototype.size
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]size\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of \f[CR]Set\f[R]
instances returns the number of (unique) elements in this set.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] \f[B]set\f[R] = \f[B]new\f[R] Set();
\f[B]const\f[R] object = {};

\f[B]set\f[R].add(42);
\f[B]set\f[R].add(\(dqforty two\(dq);
\f[B]set\f[R].add(\(dqforty two\(dq);
\f[B]set\f[R].add(object);

console.log(\f[B]set\f[R].size);
\f[I]// Expected output: 3\f[R]
.EE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The value of \f[CR]size\f[R] is an integer representing how many entries
the \f[CR]Set\f[R] object has.
A set accessor function for \f[CR]size\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R]; you
cannot change this property.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using size
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] mySet = \f[B]new\f[R] Set();
mySet.add(1);
mySet.add(5);
mySet.add(\(dqsome text\(dq);

console.log(mySet.size); \f[I]// 3\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Set\f[R]
